Recall: \(r_t=\ln\left(\frac{P_t}{P_{t-1}}\right)\)

The log-normal model assumes \(r_t\)s are \(i.i.d.\) and \(N(\mu,\sigma^2)\)

\[r_t(k)=\ln\left(\frac{P_t}{P_{t-k}}\right)=r_{t-k+1}+\cdots+r_{t-1}+r_t\]

under the log-normal model \(r_t(k) \sim N(k\mu,k\sigma^2)\)

so \(1+R_t(k)=e^{r_t(k)} \sim \text{log normal }(k\mu,k\sigma^2)\)

\[\begin{align} P(1+R_t(k) \leq x) &= P(r_t(k) \leq \ln(x))\\ &= \Phi\left(\frac{\ln(x)-k\mu}{\sqrt{k}\cdot\sigma}\right) \end{align}\]

Example

Suppose \(r_t \sim N(0.02,0.2^2)\). What is the 3-period gross return is at most 80%?

\[P(1+R_t(3) \leq 0.8)=\Phi\left(\frac{\ln(0.8)-3\times 0.02}{\sqrt{3}\times 0.2}\right)\approx 20.686\%\]

\[\text{E}(1+R_t(3))=e^{0.06+\frac{3(0.2)^2}{2}}\approx 1.1275\]

\[\text{Var}(1+R_t(3))=(e^{3(0.2)^2}-1)e^{2(0.06)+3(0.2)^2}\approx 0.16208\]

Aside on Random Walks:

\(Z_1,Z_2,\cdots\) are \(i.i.d.\) with mean \(\mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2\)

Let \(S_0\) be an initial starting point

Let \(S_t=S_0+Z_1+Z_2+\cdots+Z_t\) where \(t=1,2,3,\cdots\)

\(\{S_t\}_{t=0}^\infty\) is a random walk process

\(\{S_t\}_{t=1}^\infty\) is the step process

\[Z_t= \left\{\begin{array}{l} +1 & ,\text{w.p. }p\\ -1 & ,\text{w.p. }1-p \end{array}\right.\]

\[\text{E}(S_t|S_0)=s_0+\mu t\]

\[\text{Var}(S_t|S_0)=\sigma^2t\]

If \(Z_t \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)\), then \(\{S_t\}_{t=0}^\infty\) is called a normal random walk

\[P(S_t \in (S_0+\mu t)\pm Z_{\frac{\alpha}{2}}\sigma\sqrt{t}\ |S_0)=1-\alpha\]

\[S_t|S_0 \sim N(S_0+\mu t,\sigma^2t)\]

If \(\{S_t\}_{t=0}^\infty\) is a random walk process, then \(\{e^{S_t}\}_{t=0}^\infty\) is called a geometric (exponential) random walk

\[e^{S_t}=e^{S_0}\times e^{Z_1}\times\cdots\times e^{Z_t}\]

If \(Z_t \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)\), then \(\{e^{S_t}\}_{t=0}^\infty\) is called a log-normal geometric random walk

Connection with log gross return:

recall \(\ln\left(\frac{P_t}{P_{t-k}}\right)=r_{t-k+1}+\cdots+r_t=r_t(k)\), where \(r_t(k)\) is k-period log gross return

put \(k=t\): \(\frac{P_t}{P_0}=r_1+\cdots+r_t=r_t(t)\)

If \(r_1,r_2,\cdots\) are \(i.i.d.\) with mean \(\mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2\), then \(r_t(t)=r_1+\cdots+r_t\) is a random walk starting at 0

also, \(\ln(P_t)=\ln(P_0)+r_1+\cdots+r_t\) is a random walk starting at \(\ln(P_0)\)

so \(\{P_t\}_{t=0}^\infty\) is a geometric random walk with parameters \(\mu\) and \(\sigma^2\)

\(\text{E}(P_t|P_0)=P_0\cdot e^{\mu t+\frac{\sigma^2t}{2}}\), median \((P_t|P_0)=P_0\cdot e^{\mu t}\) since \(P_t=P_0\cdot \underbrace{e^{r_1+\cdots+r_t}}_\text{log normal}\)

Two Important Questions:

  1. Are the returns normally distributed?
  2. Are the returns independent?

Normal Probability Plots:

Suppose \(X_1,\cdots,X_n\) is a sample from a normal population

Let \(X_{(1)},\cdots,X_{(n)}\) be the “order statistics”, smallest to largest

\(X_{(i)}\) estimates the \(\frac{i}{n+1}\) - quantile of the distribution

If the distribution is normal, then \(X_{(i)} \approx \mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{i}{n+1}\right)\), where \(\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{i}{n+1}\right)\) is the quantile of \(N(0,1)\) distribution

so if we plot \(X_{(i)}\) v.s. \(\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{i}{n+1}\right)\), and if the distribution is normal, the plot should be roughly a straight line

alternatively, plot \(X_{(i)}\) v.s. \(\text{E}(Z_{(i)})\) where \(Z_1,\cdots,Z_n\) is a sample from \(N(0,1)\)

v.s. \(\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{i-\frac{1}{2}}{n}\right)\)

Types of Deviation from Normality: (\(X_{(i)}\) v.s. \(\Phi^{-1}\left(\frac{i-\frac{1}{2}}{n}\right)\))

  1. convex (left-skewed)
  1. concave (right-skewed)
  1. convex-concave (heavier-tails than normal)
  1. concave-convex (lighter-tails than normal)

standardized skewness:

\[\text{E}\left[\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^3\right]=\text{sk}\]

standardized kurtosis:

\[\text{E}\left[\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^4\right]=\text{kur}\]

Jarque-Bera Test:

\[\text{JB}=n\left[\frac{(\hat{\text{sk}})^2}{6}+\frac{(\hat{\text{kur}}-3)^2}{24}\right] \sim \chi^2_2 \quad \text{asymptotically}\]
